IRS990.ActivityOrMissionDesc: ASSISTANCE LEAGUE OF DENVER IS A NONPROFIT VOLUNTEER ORGANIZATION SERVING CHILDREN AND ADULTS THROUGH ITS PHILANTHROPIC PROGRAMS.
IRS990.MissionDesc: ASSISTANCE LEAGUE OF DENVER IS A NONPROFIT VOLUNTEER ORGANIZATION SERVING CHILDREN AND ADULTS THROUGH ITS PHILANTHROPIC PROGRAMS.
IRS990.Desc: Assistance League Schools Program was adopted during 2019-20, where all the programs for children were provided to 740 students at Boston K-8 in Aurora and Valverde Elementary in Denver. Assistance League Schools was expanded to include 8 schools and served 2,702 students in fiscal 2023. This program meets the Chapters goals of having a substantial impact on those we serve by collaborating with school personnel to provide Operation School Bell, fine arts programs, family enrichment, literacy programs, teacher appreciation and other needs of the schools and families.

ProgSrvcAccomActy2Grp.Desc: Hospital Equipment Lending Program (HELP) served the community by loaning out 5,065 pieces of durable medical equipment (wheelchairs, walkers, bath benches, etc.) free of charge to 3,283 people in need. Individuals are referred to our program by physical therapists, hospital staff, visiting nurses and other community resources.

ProgSrvcAccomActy3Grp.Desc: Operation School Bell is now included in Assistance League Schools and is being phased out as a stand-alone program. During fiscal 2023, Operation School Bell provided 1,617 non-ALD School students and 2,702 ALD School students with new school clothes and distributed 3,500 health kits and 7,000 books. All participating schools are Title 1 Denver Public School and Aurora Public School students.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: Part V, Line 4: Intended uses of the endowment fund.
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: THE PURPOSE OF THE ENDOWMENT FUND IS TO PROVIDE A FINANCIAL RESOURCE TO SUPPORT FUTURE GENERATIONS.

THE CHAPTER HAS APPLIED THE PROVISIONS OF THE FASB'S ASC 740-10, ACCOUNTING FOR UNCERTAINTY IN INCOME TAXES. UNDER ASC 740-10, NONPUBLIC ENTERPRISES, INCLUDING NONPROFIT ORGANIZATIONS, ARE REQUIRED TO RECORD A TAX LIABILITY WHEN SUBSTANTIAL UNCERTAINTIES EXIST AS TO WHETHER CERTAIN INCOME IS EXEMPT FROM REDERAL, STATE AND LOCAL INCOME TAX. AS OF MAY 31, 2023 AND 2022, THE CHAPTER HAD NO SUBSTANTIAL UNCERTAIN INCOME TAX POSITIONS.

OTHER PROGRAM SERVICES 4: Scholarships were awarded to 28 students in need of financial aid at Community College of Denver and Pickens Technical College. Each college financial aid office screens all applicants and refers those who meet specific requirements. The funding may be used for tuition, student fees and books. We served fewer students this year and increased the scholarship amount for greater impact. OTHER PROGRAM SERVICES 5: Arts for Kids funded art programs at the Assistance League Schools and two Operation School Bell schools, introducing students to programs such as classical music, opera, theater, dance, and storytelling. OTHER PROGRAM SERVICES 6: Assault Survivor Kits (ASK) offered new clothing and toiletry bags to 819 victims of rape/sexual assault brought to Colorado hospitals with SANE (Sexual Assault Nurse Examiner) Programs. By supplying bundles of clothing and toiletries for victims, a sense of caring and dignity is restored. The Chapter currently serves Denver Health, St. Anthony Hospital System, Centura Frisco and University of Colorado (Aurora, Highlands Ranch). We also supplied 200 pair of ladies panties for use by clients of Samaritan House. OTHER PROGRAM SERVICES 7: ALD-O Bears were distributed to paramedics and University of Colorado Hospital, Department of Pediatrics Radiation Oncology, where they were given to 500 traumatized children in need of comfort. OTHER PROGRAM SERVICES 8: The Serves Our Seniors program provided social activities and companionship that enhanced the quality of life for 162 residents at Cherrelyn Healthcare Center, a local Medicaid nursing facility. OTHER PROGRAM SERVICES 9: Hospitality House prepared hot meals and sack lunches for 4,080 seniors in the Denver metro area.at the Senior Support Center, The Gathering Place, Urban Peak, Marian Plaza, and Cathedral Plaza. Blessings in a Backpack provided twice monthly non-perishable food items in backpacks for two Aurora Public Schools, benefiting over 1,050 students. Senior Bingo and a free lunch was restarted after a 3-year COVID hiatus, with 720 seniors participating. OTHER PROGRAM SERVICES 10: The We-Share Program redistributes unsold items and equipment donations to charities for the direct benefit of those in need. We donate crutches to Crutches for Africa, clothing to the Senior Resource Center and the Aurora Welcome Center, and bedding and linens to the Humane Society, to name a few. In fiscal 2023, $36,752 of equipment and clothing were passed on to other nonprofit organizations for the benefit of their clients. Items are valued at Thrift Shop value or for medical equipment, 50 percent of original cost.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: Form 990, Part VI, Section A, Line 6
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: MEMBERS SHALL BE CALLED VOTING MEMBERS AND NONVOTING MEMBERS. MEMBERS WHO CHOOSE TO ATTEND ALL BUSINESS MEETINGS WHERE VOTES ARE TAKEN ARE DESIGNATED AS VOTING MEMBERS. MEMBERS WHO CHOOSE NOT TO ATTEND THE BUSINESS MEETINGS ARE DESIGNATED AS NONVOTING MEMBERS AND ARE NOT COUNTED IN THE QUORUM.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: Form 990, Part VI, Section A, Line 7a
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: VOTING MEMBERS ELECT THE GOVERNING BOARD.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: Form 990, Part VI, Section A, Line 7b
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: VOTING MEMBERS ARE MADE AWARE OF ANYTHING THAT CONCERNS TIME OR MONEY. MEMBERS APPROVE THE ADOPTION OF A NEW OR DELETION OF AN EXISTING PROGRAM. VOTING MEMBERS ALSO APPROVE THE BUDGET.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: Form 990, Part VI, Section B, Line 11b
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: THE FORM 990 OF THE CHAPTER IS PRESENTED TO THE BOARD AND MEMBERSHIP FOR REVIEW AND APPROVAL PRIOR TO FILING. IT IS THEN SIGNED BY THE CHAPTER'S PRESIDENT AND FILED WITH THE IRS.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: Form 990, Part VI, Section B, Line 12c
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: EACH BOARD MEMBER IS GIVEN A COPY OF THE CONFLICT OF INTEREST POLICY YEARLY AND DISCLOSES ANY CONFLICTS OR POTENTIAL CONFLICTS. BOARD MEMBERS ARE ASKED TO NOTIFY THE BOARD IF ANY POTENTIAL CONFLICTS COME UP DURING THE YEAR. THESE ARE KEPT ON FILE AT THE CHAPTER'S OFFICIAL ADDRESS.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: Form 990, Part VI, Section C, Line 19
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: THE CHAPTER'S GOVERNING DOCUMENTS, CONFLICT OF INTEREST POLICY, FINANCIAL STATEMENTS AND FORM 990 ARE AVAILABLE TO THE PUBLIC UPON REQUEST. THE FINANCIAL STATEMENTS AND FORM 990 ARE ALSO AVAILABLE ON THE CHAPTER'S WEBSITE.
